	<a name="origin"></a>
	<h3>1. Origin of the subcellular localization data</h3>
	
	<p align="justify">The subcellular localizations of the proteins could be experimentally verified, predicted by computational methods or from unknown origin.
		<ul>
			<li><b>Experimental:</b> subcellular localizations deriving from experiments often contain sub-organelle specific information for the proteins.
			This means that the definition of the localization data is high, the localization of the protein could be e.g. in certain protein complexes.</li>
			<li><b>Predicted:</b> subcellular localizations deriving from computational prediction methods based on less specific predictors of localization,
			such as the search for Nuclear Localization Signals (NLS) to predict the nuclear localization of a given protein.
			Because of this lower specificity the definition of the predictions often reach only the level of major cell organelles, such as the nucleus or the cytoplasm.</li>
			<li><b>Unknown:</b> subcellular localizations from unknown origin also may occur. The definition of those data could vary between source databases.</li>
		</ul>
	</p>


	<br/><a name="structure"></a>
	<h3>2. Structure of the subcellular localization data</h3>
	
	<p align="justify">Subcellular localizations were standardized based on
	<a href="http://www.geneontology.org/GO.component.guidelines.shtml">Gene Ontology (GO) cellular component terms</a>
	arranged with manual curation into a non-redundant localization tree with more than 1600 individual GO terms.
	The localization tree contains only the GO cellular component terms, which the ComPPI database contains.
	For more details <a href="http://bificomp2.sote.hu:22422/comppi/files/85e7056adb541d5a18c60792457986c71a3a0ab0/databases/loctree/loctree.textile">visit the whole localization tree.</a></p>
	
	<p align="justify">The difference in the definition of the localization data
	and the ability to deal with a usable number of localizations for the scoring based filtering method indicate the relevance of the separation of subcellular localization
	data into major and minor localization fractions.</p>
			
	<p align="justify">Based on the localization tree of the GO terms we have arranged the minor localizations into 6 big cellular components
	(cytoplasm, nucleus, mitochondrion, secretory-pathway, membrane, extracellular).
	For more details <a href="http://bificomp2.sote.hu:22422/comppi/files/85e7056adb541d5a18c60792457986c71a3a0ab0/databases/loctree/largelocs.yml">visit the list of minor localizatons belonging to major cellular components.</a></p>
	
	<p>The distribution of the branches in the tree shows how many minor localizations (GO terms) were assigned to a certain major localization:
		<ul>
			<li>cytoplasm: 525</li>
			<li>nucleus: 353</li>
			<li>mitochondrion: 78</li>
			<li>secretory-pathway: 185</li>
			<li>membrane: 367</li>
			<li>extracellular: 126</li>
		</ul>
	</p>


	<br/><a name="expsystype"></a>
	<h3>3. Experimental system type of the subcellular localization data</h3>
	
	<p>The differences in the <a href="#origin">origin</a> of the subcellular localization data indicate that we had to arrange the system types into
	experimental (1), predicted (2), and unknown (0) origin. To learn more about our system types navigate
	<a href="http://bificomp2.sote.hu:22422/comppi/files/85e7056adb541d5a18c60792457986c71a3a0ab0/databases/systemtypes/system.csv">here</a>.</p>
	
	<p>Because of the redundancy in the nomenclature of the system types we had to map the synonyms into a common name. To learn more about our system type synonyms navigate
	<a href="http://bificomp2.sote.hu:22422/comppi/files/85e7056adb541d5a18c60792457986c71a3a0ab0/databases/systemtypes/synonym.csv">here</a>.</p>
	
	<p>The subcellular localization data from the Gene Ontology is one of our biggest resources.
	ComPPI classifies the GO cellular component annotations by <a href="http://www.geneontology.org/GO.evidence.shtml">evidence level</a>,
	which allows us to deal with a more detailed subcellular localization dataset.</p>
	
	<p>The structure of the GO evidence levels and the meaning of the abbreviations in the source data:
	<ul>
		<li>Experimental</li>
			<ul>
				<li>EXP: Inferred from Experiment</li>
				<li>IDA: Inferred from Direct Assay</li>
				<li>IPI: Inferred from Physical Interaction</li>
				<li>IMP: Inferred from Mutant Phenotype</li>
				<li>IGI: Inferred from Genetic Interaction</li>
				<li>IEP: Inferred from Expression Pattern</li>
			</ul>
		<li>Predicted</li>
			<ul>
				<li>ISS: Inferred from Sequence or Structural Similarity</li>
				<li>ISO: Inferred from Sequence Orthology</li>
				<li>ISA: Inferred from Sequence Alignment</li>
				<li>ISM: Inferred from Sequence Model</li>
				<li>IGC: Inferred from Genomic Context</li>
				<li>IBA: Inferred from Biological aspect of Ancestor</li>
				<li>IBD: Inferred from Biological aspect of Descendant</li>
				<li>IKR: Inferred from Key Residues</li>
				<li>IRD: Inferred from Rapid Divergence</li>
				<li>RCA: inferred from Reviewed Computational Analysis</li>
			</ul>
		<li>Unknown</li>
			<ul>
				<li>TAS: Traceable Author Statement</li>
				<li>NAS: Non-traceable Author Statement</li>
				<li>IC: Inferred by Curator</li>
				<li>ND: No biological Data available</li>
				<li>IEA: Inferred from Electronic Annotation</li>
				<li>NR: Not Recorded</li>
			</ul>
	</ul>
	</p>
	
